tists he described in the two editions of his Lives, placing these reflections in their contemporary context and later developments in art history and criticism. The result is an important appraisal of Vasari’s achievement, which despite its imperfections is without parallel in the history of Western art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aArt historianszItalyvBiography. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aArezzo:.  aClement VII, Pope (Giulio de’ Medici).  aCortona.  aFrancia, Francesco.  aGenga, Girolamo.  aGiuliano da Maiano.  aGuillaume de Marcillat.  aJulius II, Pope.  aLeo X, Pope (Cardinal Giovanni de Medici).  aLeonardo da Vinci.  aLondon: National Gallery.  aMedici, de’: family.  aMontaguti: family.  aPasserini, Cardinal Silvio.  aPerugia.  aPiero della Francesca.  aPollastra, Giovanni.  aRaphael (Raffaello Sanzio).  aRobbia, Luca della.  aSignorelli: Egidio.  aTacci, Maddalena dei.  aUrbino.  aVasari: Antonio (brother).  aViti, Timoteo.  a—Churches: S. Agostino.  a—Vatican: Belvedere.  a—works: Creation of Adam.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertThe A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Packagez978311129290840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691252223?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691252223423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691252223/original  a978-3-11-129290-8  The A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles